<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-485-051  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 485 051.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 8 1990 v7 n40 p87(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-tech witch-hunting vs. First Amendment. (Electronic FrontierFoundation protecting legal rights of computer users) (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whitmore, Sam.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ComputersLegal IssuesComputer HackersUser BehaviorComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>It's show time for the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), the non-profitorganization recently formed to ensure that the U.S.andP;  government doesn'tsubvert the Constitution in its zeal to prosecute computer criminals.andM;Co-founded by Mitch Kapor, founder of Lotus and On Technology, and GratefulDead lyricist and author John Perry Barlow, the EFF hopes to prevent thehigh-tech witch-hunting that characterized the FBI's efforts to identify theNuPrometheus league, the group that stole and disseminated Apple's MacintoshROM code in 1989.andP;  Dozens of people lost their computers and modems to FBIagents who, according to the EFF, made the gestapo look like Jehovah'sWitnesses.andM;The EFF aims to protect First Amendment rights by clarifying what is meant by&quot;hacker,&quot; a once-benign term referring to a technically inclined individualwho could get a computer to do things the average person couldn't.andP;  Today,asserts the EFF, &quot;hacker&quot; has come to mean &quot;computer criminal.&quot;andM;Kapor and Barlow have begun hiring a full-time staff to pressure the SecretService, FBI and other agencies to investigate computer crimes legally andrespectfully.andP;  We hope it succeeds.andM;Government prosecutors do have good reason to fear computer criminals; theycan steal bank-account passwords, snarl air traffic and sabotage acorporation's payroll, all in a day's work.andP;  Such criminals must certainly beprosecuted.andM;But the EFF fears -- with reason -- that the government, unchecked by alargely PC-ignorant public, will increasingly violate the First Amendment byspying on private, modem-based communications, and will interrogate hackerswithout a shred of due process.andM;One reason the Feds might be overreacting is the thought that hackers mayfind their way into, say, the TRW database, which contains every singletransaction tracked to one's Social Security number.andP;  And there may bedirtier digital secrets lurking elsewhere.andM;That the government wants to make examples of hackers is neither surprisingnor unwelcome, just so long as the prosecutors stop on this side of theConstitution.andP;  -- Sam Whitmore</TEXT></DOC>